  "Cannot assign to read only property 'message' of object 'SyntaxError: /App.jsx: Adjacent JSX elements must be wrapped in an enclosing tag. Did you want a JSX fragment &lt;&gt;...&lt;/&gt;? (4:4)\n\n  2 |   return (\n  3 |     &lt;h2&gt;Authors&lt;/h2&gt;\n&gt; 4 |     &lt;ul&gt;\n    |     ^\n  5 |       &lt;li&gt;Tyler McGinnis&lt;/li&gt;\n  6 |       &lt;li&gt;Ben Adam&lt;/li&gt;\n  7 |       &lt;li&gt;Alex Brown&lt;/li&gt;'": "",
  "That's a fancy way to say that you can only ever return one top-level element from a component. In our example, we're trying to return 2 (\u0000SKIP#145\u0000, and \u0000SKIP#146\u0000).": "",
  "To fix this, as the error says, we want to return one, which we can do by wrapping everything in a \u0000SKIP#147\u0000.": "",
  "That fixes the issue, but now we have a semantic problem.": "",
  "Now we're unnecessarily creating an extra \u0000SKIP#151\u0000. This is the exact use case that \u0000SKIP#152\u0000 was created for. If you want to return adjacent elements but don't want to change your markup, wrap them in \u0000SKIP#153\u0000.": "",
  "Much better.": "",
  "Let's do another one. Can you spot what's wrong with this JSX?": "",
  "If you're familiar with HTML but new to React, your answer is probably \"...nothing?\" This is another case where JSX is slightly different than the HTML spec. Whenever you have a \"Self-closing tag\" (the most popular being \u0000SKIP#162\u0000, \u0000SKIP#163\u0000, and \u0000SKIP#164\u0000), you need to make sure that you explicitly close them.": "",
  "So with that, our \u0000SKIP#166\u0000 component will now have valid JSX if we explicitly close all our self-closing elements.": "",
  "How about this one? Can you spot what's wrong with this JSX?": "",
  "I know, this is a weird one. The error is that \u0000SKIP#169\u0000 should be \u0000SKIP#170\u0000.": "",
  "The reason for this is because, as you know, eventually this JSX gets converted into JavaScript, and in JavaScript, there are particular keywords that are reserved (meaning you can't use them). \u0000SKIP#172\u0000 just happens to be one of those.": "",
